column169: Provide more training to dock personnel on proper techniques for protecting freight for transit.

column168: On June 1, 2022, one (1) 15-gallon drum containing corrosive liquid was damaged during transit and released approximately ten (10) gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC, who dispatched a crew from TPM Group (TPM) to perform the necessary corrective action. TPM overpacked the damaged drum, then utilized neutralizer and absorbents to remediate the impacted surface.

column168: While loading pallets into an outbound trailer, a Veolia material handler struck a carboy on a protruding piece of metal in the trailer causing a small gash in the side of the carboy.  Approximately 4 gallons of liquid spilled to the trailer floor and then to the ground.  The drum was overpacked and the spill was cleaned using absorbent pads and oil dry.
column169: The material handler was reminded to be more careful and pay attention when loading drums into a trailer.

column168: The drums were picked up from the customer's site by Veolia personnel and the shipment was driven to Veolia's Fredericksburg 10 day intransit facility. Upon arrival at the facility, the Veolia employee opened the back of the truck and noticed an odor. The drums were again inspected as the truck was unloaded. A small pinhole was discovered on the bottom of a 551A2DM that caused 200ml of Acetone onto the floor of the truck. The drum showed no signs of corrosion or debris on the truck floor that could have caused the damage. The spill was cleaned and the drum was overpacked into a 851A2DM without further incident.
column169: Veolia employees were reminded to perform a more thorough inspection of the drums before leaving the generators location.

column168: Upon arrival to the consignee location, it was discovered that the container was leaking inside the trailer. The investigation revealed that the drum had a small puncture hole caused by a protruding nail in the skid. The container was immediately turned on it's side to prevent further release of material. Once safely contained the drum was accepted by the customer and placed into another container. Due to the customer being in possession of the container we are unable to provide the packaging specifications.
column169: This incident may have been prevented had the drum been loaded on a skid free from protruding nails. Using pallets free from nails and protruding objects is a regular topic covered in dock safety meetings. This topic will continue to be covered to prevent future occurrences.

column168: FULLY LABELED HAZ-MAT SHIPMENT WAS VISUALLY DISCOVERED WET IN APPEARANCE BY AN UNLOADER IN SECTION-D. WITHOUT TOUCHING THE PKG HE EVACUATED THE AREA AND NOTIFIED HIS IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR. DMP WAS CONTACTED AND WITHIN A MINUTE A RESPONDER ARRIVED, DONNING THE PROPER PPE. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE CAPS ON 2 OF 4 PLASTIC 1-GAL JUGS WERE LOOSE BY 1/2 ROTATION, CAUSING A TOTAL OF 12 OUNCES TO LEAK THROUGH THE BREACHES AND INTO THE BASE AND SIDE WALLS OF THE CARTON. THERE WAS NO INTERNAL PACKING MATERIAL AND THE OUTER CARTON WAS A DOUBLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT A 44 LBS/INCH EDGE CRUSH TEST (ECT).

column168: PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED ON IN THE OUTBOUNDS AFTER IT TRAVELED UP A PRIMARY SORTER. WHEN IT MOVED THROUGH THE SYSTEM IT WAS DAMAGED. ITEMS FROM THE PACKAGE WERE FOUND ON ONE SORTER AND THEY CALLED THE PSC FOR A RESPONDER TO PICK IT UP. THE DESIGNATED RESPONDER LEFT IMMEDIATELY WEARING FULL PPE AND HAD A FULLY STOCKED SPILL CART. THE SORTER HAS A MAJOR VOLUME OF PACKAGE FLOW, AND MAINTENANCE WAS CALLED TO THE SPILL TO LOCK OUT THE EQUIPMENT FROM THE LEAKER GOING INTO THE MACHINERY. MAINTENANCE WAS NOTIFIED TO LOCKOUT THE EQUIPMENT AND REMOVE THE GUARDS IN ORDER SO THAT THE RESPONDER COULD CLEAN UP THE SPILLED HAZMAT. THE DESIGNATED RESPONDER REFERRED TO THE CURRENT DECISION TREE AND APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS. THEN THE RESPONSE ACTION AND DECONTAMINATION PROCEDURES WERE FOLLOWED FOR THE CLEAN UP AND THE PACKAGE/DEBRIS GOT BROUGHT BACK TO THE PSC. THE PACKAGE AND DEBRIS WERE PROCESSED USING THE WASTE DISPOSAL CHART FOR FULL DMP.

column168: At 0735 ET, XPO Logistics terminal, LDA notified ERTS of a release of UN1805 Phosphoric Acid from a 275 gallon tote due to a forklift puncture, impacting the dock. Oil Dri was put down as a barrier. ERTS dispatched Lone Star Hazmat to conduct cleanup. At 0933 ET, Lone Star personnel arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 125 gallons of product released to a 75' x 50' area of the concrete dock floor and a 30' x 30' area of the asphalt lot below. Soda ash and absorbents were deployed and worked into the impacted areas to collect and neutralize the material. The remaining product in the damaged tote was pumped into a new tote. The damaged tote was then cut up and containerized along with all waste into (9) 55 gallon poly drums. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

Forklift operator was unloading freight when the skid slipped back onto the forks and caused the tear into (1) (50-lb.) bag resulting in a (1) lb. release onto the dock. The spill was cleaned and material placed into an overpack for proper disposal.

column168: On June 15, 2022 United Vision Logistics contacted ERTS regarding a corrosive liquid release that occurred at Kurita, 34523 Terminal Court, Geismar, LA. It was advised that up to 150 gallons of product released when an unknown container fell off a load on the entrance road leading into the facility. At the time of the report, no drains or waterways were reported to have been impacted. ERTS dispatched AMPOL (environmental contractor) for response and remedial operations. AMPOL personnel arrived on site and advised that site personnel already transferred the remaining product into a new IBC. AMPOL personnel reported that approximately 50 gallons released to a 30ft x 30ft area on concrete and a 30ft x 5ft area of adjacent grass. Site personnel and first responders contained the release with granular absorbents. AMPOL personnel applied soda ash to the impacted area of concrete and collected the wastes for pending disposal. AMPOL personnel excavated the impacted grass and soil and those final restoration operations are pending at this time. All wastes generated were collected and taken off site for pending disposal.

column168: Driver was working around construction equipment. He threw 2 - 20' hoses under their trailer. He was able to hook to one hydrant but the second hose was caught under the construction trailer. He walked around to free it up and while on that side of the trailer he connected the second hose to the trailer, forgetting about not having hooked one hose to a drop hydrant. He started the flow of product and realized he hadn't linked the second hose when he saw product flowing on the ground. He immediately stopped flow and started to contain the product. Driver used spill kits and socks in the flow channel and covered the storm drain with a mat. Product was contained to a hard surface and did not enter any waterways.
column169: Driver was reminded of standard operating procedure which includes doing a double check that all hoses are secured to hydrants prior to turning on the flow of product. Driver was required to review and retrain in the Petroleum SOP for Safe Loading and Unloading.

column168: The packages are generally designed to be lifted from the top of the package. In this case, they were being transported by a van trailer and were placed onto a pallet. The pallet chosen was not sturdy enough to fully support the bag, and there were large spaces between the slats on the pallet. The weight of the bag crushed down parts of the pallet, and caused sections of the bag to sag into the void space between the pallet slats, down into the space used to move the pallet. When the forklift was used to lift the pallet, the forks punctured the bag, causing the release. The pallet and bag were placed into a temporary containment and an inhouse response team was called in to repackage the contents into drums.
column169: We have provided examples of sturdier pallets that have minimal to no spacing between the wooden slats, as well as plastic pallets that have no spacing to the customer for use with these bags. Customer has also indicated that they will switch to a smaller size of 13H3 bag, which will limit the volume and help minimize the weight per package.

column168: RESPONDED TO A DECLARED LEAKING PACKAGE MARKED AND LABELED UN1987 ALCOHOLS N.O.S WITH DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPPING PAPERS. OVERPACK INDICATED ON THE OUTER BOX. PACKAGE HAD BEEN ACCEPTANCE AUDITED AT ORIGIN. UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS DISCOVERED (3) 1 GALLON JUGS WITH (2) LEAKING SMALL AMOUNTS FROM THEIR CLOSURES. THE CONTAINERS WERE INDIVIDUALLY CONTAINED IN CLEAR BAGS AND HAD TAPE OVER THEIR CAPS. THE LEAK FROM ONE JUG WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE SEALED BAG. THE LEAK OF THE SECOND JUG HAD LEAKED ONTO THE CARTON BUT THE SMALL AMOUNT EVAPORATED. LAST JUG DID NOT LEAK. NO UN SPECIFICATION CODES FOUND ON THE INNER CONTAINERS.

column168: SequenceEvent: The paint can was found leaking out of its outer packaging due to the loose lid with no paint clips. The package was then brought to QA for further inspection. DescribePack: The paint can had no paint clips to help properly seal the lid, so therefore the lid came off and leaked out all product. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: The package was contained in a lined hazmat drum.

SequenceEvent: PACKAGE TAKEN OUT OF SYSTEM FLOW DUE TO SPILL, ALL CONTENTS CONTAINED IN LINED TOTE DescribePack: CAP LOOSE, SECURE TAPE FAILED TO KEEP CAP SECURE DurationRel: 0 and MitigateEffect: BOTTLE PLACED UPRIGHT,  PLACED IN PROCESSING AREA

SequenceEvent: PACKAGETAKEN OUT OF SYSTEM FLOW DUE TO SPILL, ALL CONTENTS CONTAINED IN LINED TOTE DescribePack: SECURE TAPE FAILING CAUSING CAP TO LEAK, NO MARKINGS ON BOX FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUID/ UNDECLARED HAZMAT DurationRel: 0 and MitigateEffect: BOTTLE PLACED UPRIGHT,  PLACED IN PROCESSING AREA

SequenceEvent: Package was discovered at the QA area. Package was wet and opened. Upon inspection while wearing gloves, it appears that one of the contents were missing. DescribePack: Package may have been mishandled. Package had tape that wasn't secured, causing one of the bottles to have fallen off. DurationRel: 0 and MitigateEffect: I went to clean up the spill by using the absorbent pads while wearing gloves.

DescribePack: A missing cap and failed inner seal allowed liquid to leak during transit wetting and staining the contents and carton. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Pkg placed in unlined tote.

column168: SequenceEvent: LID NOT SECURE ON PAINT CANS CAUSING A LOT OF LIQUID TO LEAK OUT.SPILL CLEANED UP WITH FOLD ABSORBENT AND PUT IN HAZMAT BAG AND DRUM DescribePack: LOOSE LID ON PAINT CANS DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: SPILL CLEANED UP WITH FOLD ABSORBENT ROLLS AND PUT IN HAZMAT BAG AND DRUM

SequenceEvent: MANAGER NOTIFIED QA THAT THE PACKAGE WAS LEAKING. THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED IN A TOTE LINED WITH A HAZMAT BAG WHILE THE MESS WAS CLEANED UP. THE PACKAGE WAS THEN TAKEN TO THE PROCESSING CAGE. DescribePack: THE PACKAGE HAD BEEN DROPPED AND THE BOTTLE WERE CRUSHED AND LEAKING OUT SOILING THE BOX. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED IN A TOTE LINED WITH A HAZMAT BAG.

SequenceEvent: The package had no exterior markings indicating it was a hazardous product. The product was loaded into a wall and the wall fell down. The bottles opened and spilled out into the belly of the trailer. DescribePack: At least 3 of the bottles, most likely more, have leaked out almost completely. DurationRel: 5 and MitigateEffect: The damaged package was bagged and contained. The packages that got some of the acid on them have been repacked. At 1424 ET, XPO Terminal XSG called and stated that their delivery driver reported a release at a customer location in Flit, MI. It was advised one cylinder of Helium fell in the trailer due to improper blocking and bracing and was releasing an unknown amount of Helium. ERTS dispatched First Call Environmental to conduct cleanup. At 1815 ET, First Call personnel arrived onsite and located the damaged cylinder. They opened the valve and let the cylinder complete it's off gassing. The cylinder was being delivered to the site and personnel there stated they would keep the cylinder. No waste was generated.

column168: XPO terminal LDA reported a release of Bestolife Copper Based Production Compound due to an overturned metal tote. ERTS dispatched Lone Star Hazmat to conduct cleanup. At 0025 ET, contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 100 gallons of product released to a 40' x 50' area of the dock floor due to damage to the tote valve. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: XPO Logistics Terminal NCH called in to report a spill of an unknown product impacting their trailer floor. ERTS dispatched Hepaco to conduct cleanup.  At 0815 ET, Hepaco personnel arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 3 gallons of UN3149 "Synergex" released from a 55 gallon poly drum due to impact with an adjacent pallet. The release impacted a 3' x 3' area of the trailer floor. The material was diluted with water multiple times until the pH of the trailer floor reached 6. The damaged drum was placed into an 85 gallon poly drum and all cleanup debris placed into a 55 gallon poly drum. A temperature gun was used and observation of the drums was conducted to ensure no reaction was occurring inside the waste containers. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column168: On 06/21/2022 at 1530 hours EST CSXT personnel in the Florence Yard (Florence, SC) discovered UTLX200592, a loaded tank car of Hydrogen Peroxide, Aqueous Solutions leaking from top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Solvay was notified. HEPACO,  a CSXT response contractor, responded and found the rupture disk had ruptured. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Solvay (Shawn Gleason 713-828-0251). HEPACO replaced the ruptured disk with a new 4” 80 psi disk.  The car was released back into transportation.
column169: (NAR code:1005 5 What Failed: Non-Reclosing Pressure Relief Device Where Failed: Opening in center of pressure relief device or under pressure relief cap/cover Why Failed: Frangible disc ruptured; no surge suppressor; ss expected)

column168: During routine tank car inspections, an odor was detected when looking inside the housing.  Upon further investigation, it was determined to be a vapor release at the plug on the vapor valve.  The valve was fully closed but bubbles were detected at the plug.  The plug was backed out, ensured no liquid was present and removed the plug.  There was an excessive build up of teflon tape so the plug was cleaned, retaped and reinstalled.  Before tightening the plug it was checked again with Snoop and the bubble continued.  The leak was able to be stopped with the plug.  It appears to be a defective valve leaking by and the shipper was notified and advised to apply for an OTMA.  The car was put in hold until the OTMA is granted.

column168: Austin Powder company driver Scott Cook was driving a 2007 Freightliner tractor, and pulling a non-specification pneumatic tanker in rural Caldwell county Texas around 6:00 PM on 6/1/22.  The driver had just loaded up at the company's Seguin, TX location, and was making the trip back to his home terminal in Georgetown, TX.  The driver had not yet scaled the load, but we estimate that it was around 46-47,000 of ammonium nitrate as cargo.  The driver was familiar with the road and intersection.  He was driving a truck that he was familiar with.  The trailer was a different one than he usually used, this one being slightly heavier.    The driver was negotiating a left hand turn on route 1979 (intersection with 621).  Based on telematics data the rig was taking the turn around 20 MPH.  Partway into the turn, the vehicle started to tip over.  The driver tried to right the rig, but it overturned onto its passenger side, somewhat perpendicular to the road it had just turned onto, with part of it on the pavement and part on the grass.  The latches on one of the dome lids opened due to the impact, and roughly 2 pounds of ammonium nitrate fell out onto the grass.  The weather was clear and dry, and the area was free of water, so the product was contained in the roughly 2X3 area onto which it spilled.  The driver was unhurt.  He got out of the vehicle and began his emergency response procedures, which include contacting 911, Chemtrec, and company officials.  First responders showed up directly afterwards, along with Austin Powder Company officials.  Both roads in the intersection were closed at this point.  A spill contractor was dispatched out to the scene in anticipation of more product leaking from the package.  Wreckers were dispatched, and after a period of several hours, the truck and trailer were put upright.  There was nothing for the spill contractor to clean up, and the roads were opened completely after a period of roughly 5 hours. The small amount of product (2 pounds) was given to the Austin Powder Company officials to take back to their facility.
column169: We can definitively say that this event was caused by speeding.  The driver simply took the turn too fast.  He was familiar with the intersection but simply misjudged how much needed to drop his speed.  ECMs on Austin trucks are governed by vehicle type (at a top speed).  We also utilize our telematics equipment to monitor ECM speed vs. posted speed limit.     Our corporate procedures call for counseling of drivers who are found to be chronic speeders. The driver in this incident is terminated at this point.  Our other drivers at these 2 area locations have been made aware of the accident, and the intersection in question.  It will be an area of focus that the trailer was one that he was not accustomed to pulling.  The additional weight of the trailer may have contributed toward his misjudgment of the speed he needed to maintain.  The event will be used as a training opportunity throughout our US operations.

SequenceEvent: After delivery exception, delivery driver left package on his truck instead of dropping off with QA for VSA processing.  Package was unloaded onto the conveyer instead of NC carts and was found leaking in Tower 1 chute.  Unable to determine if package was damaged before it went onto the conveyer or not.  4 1gal bottles of EcoLab EcoTemp Phase1 Detergent in product box was found with one side of the box wet and crystalized chemicals on another side.  One bottle showed signs of leaking from the cap, but the cap was not loose when tested. DescribePack: at least 1 bottle showed signs of leaking from the cap with noticable volume, but cap was not loose when tested. 1 other bottle had crystalized chemicals near the cap but did not appear to have lost any volume.  Possible leakage from package being on its side or high temps in the delivery truck and putting too much pressure on the cap causing a slow leak. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: QA notified by tower package handlers that a Hazmat had been sent up the conveyer so it could be pulled out of the chute before it spilled onto other packages.

SequenceEvent: Package was identified as being damaged after coming off of the trailer. On Thursday, June 30 at approximately 1400 hours PTRA switch crews reported a noxious odor in the Manchester yard. Slick Response was notified and responded with PTRA officers to the yard and were unable to find any indications of a release at 1500 hours. Several hours later at 1955 hours crews again reported an odor. Slick Response returned to the yard with PTRA managers and after walking several tracks responders found TILX 101045 releasing vapors from the PRD at approximately 2109 hours. The car, loaded sulfuric acid, spent, UN1832, was shipped from the Deer Park Refining LP (PEMEX) facility in Deer Park, TX. Plant personnel were notified of the vapor release from the PRD and they suggested we get the car to destination, Eco Services, approximately 2/10 of a mile from the site of the incident or we get water flowing through the coils of the car to cool the product. They also dispatched their own ER crew from SRS. PEMEX personnel suggested that the product may have a contaminant that was causing an exothermic reaction and building pressure in the tank. PTRA contacted the consignee, Eco Services, to see if they would accept the car in the current condition. They initially indicated that they would accept the car so arrangements were made to deliver the car to their facility. PTRA crews and managers moved the car to the north end of the yard across the street from Eco and requested that the gates be opened for delivery of the car. At that time the plant manager indicated that they would not be able to accept the car. Upon that notification the PTRA moved the car to a stub track adjacent to a water line where Slick Response and SRS Environmental personnel were able to connect the water line to the inlet for the coils. At that time the decision was made to shut down the yard and have all crews shelter in place at the main office building to the north of the yard until the car could be stabilized. Responders began flowing water through the coils at 0045 hours, they also vented some pressure to atmosphere to drop the pressure in the car. At that time a gauge was applied and showed an initial reading of 50 psi but it steadily began rising to 65 psi within a few minutes. With no way to control the rising pressure the decision was made to move the car approximately 7 miles to PEMEX, Deer Park Refining (the shipper) for offloading. Notifications were made to the NRC and voicemails left with FRA hazmat notifying them of the decision to move the car to PEMEX Deer Park. PTRA crews and mangers were briefed on the move, the car was secured, water lines removed and all lines closed and plugged for movement. A special train move was made to PEMEX Deer Park at 0415, the car was handed off to PEMEX Deer Park at 0510 hours.  The shelter in place at PTRA Manchester yard was lifted at 0415. No injuries were reported.

column168: On 06/30/2022 at 0833 hours EST CSXT personnel in the Hamlet Yard (Hamlet, NC) discovered UTLX200592, a loaded tank car of Hydrogen Peroxide, Aqueous Solutions leaking from top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Solvay was notified. Marion Environmental Inc, a CSXT response contractor, responded and found the rupture disk had ruptured. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Solvay (Shawn Gleason 713-828-0251). MEI placed a temporary rupture disk in the tank car. UTLX200592 does not have a surge protector in the car which is required by design. The car was placed on a Hazmat hold pending further investigation, waiting for the certificate of construction and repair records.

CLOSER NSPECTION REVEALED THAT 4 OF 4 PAINT CANS WITH CLIPS WERE DENTED TOWARD THE TOPS OF THE RECEPTICLES, CREATING BREACHES THAT CAUSED APPROX. 16 OUNCES OF THE LIQUID TO LEAK THROUGH AND INTO THE CARTON. THE INNER PACKING MATERIAL CONSISTED OF DOUBLEWALL CORRUGATED PARTITIONS AND THE OUTER CARTON WAS A DOUBLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT A 275 LBS/IN BURSTING TEST.

column168: On 06/06/2022, at 1444 hours, FRA MP&E Inspector observed in the CSXT Parkersburg Yard AXLX 3154, a loaded tank car of Sodium Hydroxide Solution, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, National Response Center, and West Virginia Department of Environmental Protection were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2022-0606-00271). Specialized Professional Services, Incorporated, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a displaced and torn manway nozzle gasket resulting in a Non-Accident Release of Hazardous Materials. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Mr. Matthew Bond of Axiall Corporation, phone 304-266-8287. Contractor personnel removed the defective gasket, installed an in-kind new replacement, and cleaned all spill material from the exterior of the car. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required.  Cause Code: 208 NARRI: 100

column168: On 07/29/2021, at 0856 hours, A FRA inspector in the CSXT Manville Yard Manville NJ discovered SHPX 222968, Loaded tank railcars of UN1993 Flammable Liquid (Acetone Toluene) ,having a Vapor  release from the vacuum relief devices. The railcars were isolated and National Response Center and the NJ Department of environment were notified. The emergency response telephone number on the waybill was contacted, (CHEMTREC Report # 2022-06-29-00130), and Veolia the shipper of record was notified. Marion Environmental a CSX response contractor was dispatched to the scene and found the vacuum relief device on both railcars having a vapor release. The Vacuum relief device was removed and replaced with a plug securing the release. The release was secured and corrective actions were communicated to the FRA, and the shipper. The railcar was placed on Hazmat hold and will require Shippers MRU to correct the defects. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required?

column168: The Advantage Tank Lines, LLC driver was delivering gasoline onto the tank trailer. The driver attempted to load too much gasoline into the trailer compartment resulting in an overfill. Approximately 100 gallons of gasoline was released. It appears there may have been an issue with the trailers overfill protection system that allowed the spill to occur. The loading facility made arrangements with an environmental contractor to respond to the scene and handle the remediation.
column169: Advantage Tank Lines, LLC will make any necessary repairs to the trailer to prevent a recurrence. Advantage Tank Lines, LLC will also continue to train and enforce safe loading/unloading policies and procedures.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

SequenceEvent: Prior to any report of spill ops manager in unload noted that inside of trailer had a strong odor. Package was not clearly label and went over top without package handlers noticing leak. Load side manager and another package handler identified package was leaking and notified QA immediately. QA put package in bin and cleaned up any and all spilled material. DescribePack: One of the four bottles had a broken security seal which is what caused liquid to be leaked. Leakage consisted of approx. 8oz. DurationRel: 2 and MitigateEffect: Product was bagged and sealed along with any remains cleaned up and disposed.

SequenceEvent: PACKAGE STARTED LEAKAGE DURING TRANSIT THEREFORE IT WAS PUT INTO A SPILLAGE BIN AND IT WAS BROUGHT TO QA. DescribePack: THE PACKAGE FAILED BECAUSE OF A LOOSE CAP. SequenceEvent: The package was recovered from the trailer leaking. The package was place at the bottom front of trailer so there were no other packages that were damaged. Upon opening the package there was paint all over the package inside and out. The package was place in a bag and placed in the hazmat area for processing. DescribePack: The seal around the paint is loose which allowed the paint to spill DurationRel: 0 and MitigateEffect: The package was removed from the area where other packages were located and place in bag and in a tote. Also made sure that the orientation arrows were followed.

SequenceEvent: A corrosive hazmat containing Protech Black Max Condenser Coil Cleaner (85-H-BM01) was discovered on loadside leaking. PPE was donned, spillage was isolated, and bagged hazmat was transported in a tote to the hazmat reporting area. SequenceEvent: Package was found at Door 1 in the unload after being unloaded from a trailer. While the package was not visibly leaking, nor was there any visible liquid inside of the trailer, the package had a loud sound of broken glass. The package was set to the side by the manager who identified the damage, and the area was cleared while the manager sought qualified assistance. Another manager arrived on scene and moved the package to a central point in unload, clear of other personnel. QA then arrived onto the scene, and  the package was placed into a lined red tote and relocated to the hazmat cage as soon as it was confirmed safe to do so. DescribePack: One of the two bottles was completely shattered. Although the outside of the box was dry at the time of inspection, one of the sides of the package had clear signs of having previously been wet. DurationRel: 0 and MitigateEffect: The area was cleared and the package was placed into a lined red tote and brought to the hazmat cage.

SequenceEvent: From a combination of FTRACK and SPIDR information, the package seems as though it was damaged before arriving to station 708. column168: At approximately 7:55 AM MST on 6/23/2022 a Veolia employee was moving a large drained 50 - 499 PCB transformer in the yard to be loaded for transportation to US Ecology. One of the forks of the lift contacted the bottom valve of the transformer below the fins and broke the valve releasing residual PCB liquids that had collected in the bottom of the transformer after draining. Approximately 1 quart of the PCB oil was released on the asphalt surface. The RQ for PCBs (1 pound) was not met. The PCB content of the transformer was listed as 210 ppm of 1260 PCB. We collected approximately 4 gallons of residual oil from the broken valve. The transformer was received as PCB Drained 50 -499 ppm.   Speedy-dry applied to the spill area to absorb any free liquid, followed by double wash with kerosene and a final wash with de-greasing detergent.    Initially three 100 cm2 wipe samples were collected from the spill area. The spill was contained, the area cleaned, and samples collected by 13:04 MST. Spill duration was approximately 5 hours. An additional 3 samples of asphalt from the spill area were also collected the following day at the request of the EPA.
column169: Verification that all drained transformers are drained and do not contain residual liquids. Re-training of Forklift Operator was performed with a reminder to take extra care when moving transformers for loading onto vehicles for shipment.

column168: On June 30, 2022, a vehicle operated by Acme Truck Line, Inc. (ATL) experienced a rollover following a single-vehicle accident. As a result, approximately twenty (20) gallons of KI-38021 released from overturned cargo to the soil surface. ATL retained Cura Emergency Services, LC (CES) to manage the environmental remediation of the site. CES dispatched a crew from Baranko Brothers Inc. (BBI) to perform the necessary corrective action. BBI personnel performed excavation operations until no visual or olfactory evidence of free product remained in the soil. All totes were returned to the warehouse. Following the excavation, BBI performed backfill and site restoration operations via clean soil and grass seed to return the area to prerelease conditions.

column168: On 6/13 at 1300, driver arrived at D&C Torching, 11014701, with LOX trailer 515303. Driver hooked up and started his delivery procedure. After cooling down the pump driver had tank pressure at 30 psi and delivered ~20 gallons. Driver heard a loud pop and thought a safety lifted. The driver shut down the delivery and secured all valves. The back cabinet tray was full of LOX and there was a large amount of vapor coming from cabinet. This made seeing anything inside very difficult. At this point the driver called his supervisor to talk through the issue. Supervisor and Mechanics looked at similar trailer at site for reference and talked through possible issues. Driver tried venting trailer and got pressure down to 15 psi but then the pressure would just build back up. With everything still secured there was still a leak happening in back of the trailer. All parties came to the conclusion it might be the inlet to the Fire Control Valve from the vessel. At this point a plan was developed to bring an empty trailer to the customer and offload 515303 into empty trailer. Second driver with new unit and Vehicle Recovery Team went to the customer. The team offloaded as much product as possible onto new unit. 515303 was then vented more and drained as much as possible to make it safe to transport. As the trailer was being offloaded, the back cabinet cleared out some the leak became visible. It was noted that the PB coil inlet flange from vessel was leaking LOX. ¿
column169: Physical inspection of vessel before closure.

column168: On June 13, 2022, Landstar notified ERTS of a 30 gallon release of Grazon P+D due to the trailer being broken into during the night.  The release impacted the inside of trailer #671931 and the asphalt parking lot. No storm drains or waterways were reported to be impacted by the release. Following contractor arrival and visual assessment, it was determined that a single 30-gallon drum spilled 30-gallons of product from a puncture at the bottom of the drum that occurred when a load shift occurred, which caused the drum to shift and subsequently be punctured by what was presumed to be a pallet nail. Media affected was limited to trailer flooring components and an underlying area of concrete. One 55-gallon poly drum contained the impacted absorbents and one 55-gallon drum contained the damaged drum.  All waste was taken off site for profiling and then disposal.

column168: ON June 13, 2022, Landstar notified ERTS of a UN2924 release in a Landstar Trailer# 698409 due to a forklift puncture. No drains or waterways were impacted by the release. Upon contractor arrival, this puncture related spill incident was confirmed and the release, estimated at 55-gallons, affected trailer flooring components and an underlying area comprised of concrete. Accordingly, the responding contractor overpacked the damaged drum and then addressed affected trailer flooring and concrete surfaces utilizing absorbents and appropriate cleaning agents.  E3 Environmental generated (3) 55-gallon drums, one containing 40 gallons of liquid product and the other 2 drums containing the impacted absorbents.  The contractor used a supersack for the contaminated pallets and one 85-gallon drum was overpacked with the damaged drum.  The contractor departed with the waste to profile and dispose of properly.

column168: On June 16, 2022, Landstar notified ERTS of a release of UN1824 "Liquid Dishmachine Detergent spill that occurred from two (2) 5-gallon plastic pails. Following contractor arrival,  it was confirmed one quart spilled due to a bad seal on the pail. The two containers of concern were containerized into a single 55-gallon DF along with affected cardboard, cut up pallet, and absorbents used to address affected trailer flooring components. All waste was staged at the contractors facility for profile and proper disposal.

The Sales and Service Representative picking up the drum from the generator failed to conduct a thorough container inspection which would have revealed a visibly corroded area on the drum body approx. 3" from the top rim of the drum. The Sales and Service Representative  used an electric drill with a socket attachment to tighten the jam nut on the closure ring. The excessive torque delivered by the electric drill caused the jam nut to squeeze the closure ring too tight and the drum body split due to the weakened integrity of the side wall caused by the corrosion resulting in approx. 19 Gal. of the material to be released to the customer's concrete dock area.
column169: The Sales and Service Representative will be held to a Corrective Action Plan that includes disciplinary action for deviation of company policy. The Sales and Service  Representative and the management team received coaching regarding the necessity to conduct thorough container inspections before handling any containers. The team will also undergo remedial training regarding thorough container inspection and proper container closure utilizing the appropriate tools and following manufacturers closure instructions.

column168: On 6/17/22 approximately@ 09:30AM SEFL freight handler was attempting to load a pallet of 4 drums containing UN 2051 onto trailer 484700 in door 23, the BTR Gonzales route for the day. The freight handler attempted to maneuver the pallet of drums onto the wall when he accidentally punctured the side of the drum causing spillage in trailer. The freight handler neglected to contain/stop the spillage by flipping the drum on it's side immediately, and at that point backed out of the trailer with the pallet and drove it up front next to the Hazmat trailer located in door 6. The Assistant SVC Manager was on the dock next to the Hazmat trailer& assisted in manuvering the drum to stop the spillage. The Assistant SVC contacted the BTR Safety Specialist informing him of the incident& the safety specialist contacted Hazmat 1. Quick dry absorbent was immediately applied on top of all spillage& blocked off the area accordingly. The Louisiana State Police DOT Officer arrived@ SEFL BTR approximately@ 11:00,and accessed the situation. USES environmental group arrived@ SEFL BTR approximately@ 12:15, accessed the situation& started the clean-up process. All chemical which had been previously covered in quick dry absorbent was cleaned up accordingly and placed into a 95 gallon containment drum. All parties, USES& Louisiana State Police left SEFL BTR approximately@ 14:00. USES will email the BTR QAL& Safety specialist all job documents upon completion.
column169: All BTR Freight Handlers will be re-trained on proper Hazmat handling in effort to mitigate damaging freight and or puncturing drums.

column168: At 1724 ET, XPO terminal NCT advised an unknown amount of UN3109 Organic Peroxide was releasing from a tote on the dock due to an unknown cause. ERTS dispatched Hepaco to conduct cleanup and containment of the material. At 1902 ET, Hepaco personnel arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 75 gallons of "Microtox Prime" released from the tote to a 40' x 40' area of the dock floor due to a puncture in the tote. A containment area was set up around the release to prevent migration. Crew began applying absorbent material to the impacted dock area. The tote was elevated and patched to slow the release. The released product was being captured inside a 55 gallon poly drum. Crew collected all free standing liquid from the dock floor and then applied more absorbents. Once the new tote was delivered the product was transferred from the damaged tote and into a new one. Wood pallet debris was removed from all waste to prevent any reaction. This material was collected into a poly bag along with absorbent material. All impacted absorbent material and the damaged cut up tote were then collected and containerized into (6) 55 gallon poly drums. Hepaco advised the bung caps were left open to relieve any pressure build up.  On June 21, 2022, at 1208 ET, Hepaco returned to evaluate the drums and advised the thermal temperature on 5 of the drums were sitting at 87-88 degrees with the floor temperature of the XPO terminal warehouse reading 82-85 degrees. However, one drum was still at 100.8 degrees so the bung was not tighten down yet. Hepaco's game plan was to give this drum another 24 hours to continue to cool down and will return for inspection. On June 22, 2022, Hepaco returned at 1808 ET and advised all drums were now sitting at 96-97 degrees and are sealed up. All waste was left onsite for XPO to manage.

column168: Dangerous goods Administration Called the station located in Loveland OH to inform them of a package in their possession suspected of containing undeclared dangerous goods. While the package had not gone out for delivery, yet, it was scheduled to be delivered the next busin6ss day. A front line employee retrieved the package and with her manager, at the request of Dangerous Goods Administration, opened the package to inspect the contents. It was reported The package with trk# 777002164485 was a small FedEx box. They opened the outer box and found green bubble wrap sealed inside. Upon opening the inner package, they found the contents to be 10 individual boxes of CCI Small Rifle primers(1000 primers total). Pictures were taken of outer packaging, inner packaging, as well as the contents both closed and open to confirm contents. There were no dangerous goods markings nor labels on any part of the packaging to indicate there was dangerous goods inside the package. Package was requested held by dangerous goods administration until further disposition.

The sound of an aerosol cans was observed by an employee and the package, a Fed Ex Pak was brought to management and when it was opened six aerosol cans of product (Zerust Axxanol spray, sprayable grease) each 340 g. column42: ELEVATED TEMPERATURE LIQUID, N.O.S., AT OR ABOVE 100 C AND BELOW ITS FLASH POINT (INCLUDING MOLTEN METALS, MOLTEN SALTS, ETC.)
column168: On 06/16/2022, at 0932 hours, personnel in the CSXT Queensgate Terminal discovered UTLX 676073, a loaded tank car of Elevated Temperature Liquid, N.O.S. (Asphalt), leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, National Response Center, and Ohio EPA were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2022-0616-00148). HEPACO, LLC, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found spilled lading on the top and sides of the tank car, 8 of 8 manway cover securement bolts less than tool tight and a displaced manway nozzle gasket in poor condition and displaced resulting in the release of lading. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Nicole Hameister of Canal Terminal Company, phone 708-516-1043. Contractor personnel installed a compatible manway gasket, secured all manway cover securement bolts in accordance with 49 CFR 173.31, and cleaned all spilled material. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required.  Cause Code: 200 NARRI: 60
column169: (NAR: 209, gasket in poor condition, NAR 200: manway bolts less than tool tight)

column168: While unloading into 2 EUG tanks with 1 vapor return line, the drop fitting on one of the tanks came loose resulting in a spill of approximately 10 gallons. Driver quickly reacted and contained most of the spill but some went into a storm water collection area, not a drain.  Our Environmental contractor was called to assess the situation.
column169: Driver was coached by the Terminal Manager and Safety staff on the proper placement of product and vapor hoses during deliveries.  He was also counseled on stop work authority when having issues

column168: Driver stated Customer normally has tank stuck and gallons that can be unloaded into tank, but today, they didn't provide that. Driver stated you cannot see in the tank to tell if its getting full or not. Paperwork was signed and tank was unlocked, driver believes about 10 gallons spilled down the tank and ran into a trench the customer had dug that goes into a ditch. Driver shut down and believes he is empty, he said he will have to blow his lines out. Driver has attempted to locate site management and make them aware of the spill and ask if they will need assistance with clean up, he took pictures and sent to TM.   Driver was released by Twin Pines Management Randy Womack and Gary Maroon
column169: Even though the Customer's tank did not have a gauging device the Driver did not verify that customer had room for product prior to unloading and did not check his paperwork.  Driver is being required to complete retraining with a Safety Training Professional.

column168: Package was discovered at the Sort Center in the Anchorage Hub on June 24 at approximately 11am. The package was then placed in a salvage drum and any residual liquid was cleaned up. The drum is being held at the hub awaiting further instructions.

Following spill cleanup, the involved package was placed inside of a salvage drum and help pending further disposition instructions.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Preparation for Transportation
column168: HazMat Dispatcher was notified by our customer that our trailer was leaking spent acid when exiting United in Warren, PA after being loaded. Our driver traveled approx. 13 miles before our office received this notification, at which time, driver was informed by dispatch to pull over on side of road and stop. Upon examination by the driver, material was in the crashbox and ~ 1/2 cup on the pavement from draintube. Driver discovered the dome gasket was not seated properly. He re-aligned it, cleaned the crashbox and rinsed the area on the pavement with water. After providing information to the City of Public Works and Warren Police, the Police gave authorization for our driver to leave. He took the trailer to our customer in Buffalo to be unloaded and then brought trailer to HazMat's shop in Lackawanna for evaluation. Although no visible defects were found, the dome gasket was removed and a new one was installed as a proactive course of action.  The local Fire Dept. in Warren spread dirt and sand on the areas that were affected.  T & R Environmental out of Bath, NY responded and remediated the contaminated areas long the driver's route. All materials that were placed on roadways to absorb the spilled acid and to help mitigate the spread were put in 2 roll-off boxes for disposal off-site.
column169: Discussion took place immediately with the driver regarding the proper process to ensure the dome gasket is seated properly and that it is secured.  Discussion took place with our customer regarding immediate notification to HazMat if our trailer is spotted leaking coming out of United (note: there is a fairly big hill to climb on way out,) as well as with any of their customers, or have them empower the site employee who notices a leak to flag our driver to stop.

A single yard box of damaged boxes and various paints and (2) 55-gallon metal drums of spent absorbents and PPE were generated.  Contractors returned to the site on June 6, 2022, to finish collecting and containerizing spent absorbents and other cleanup related material. column168: At gradual, during trash pickup, pax Timothy Wilson 13c, got my attention to show me an item I first thought was an external battery pack but turned out to be a vape device. The device was smoking. Wisps of smoke were coming from several opening in it and it was getting warm to touch. Captain was notified and FA 1 got the thermal containment bag and water , we put the device in bag and I kept putting water on it . It never flamed up, however even while drowning in water the LED indicator light on the item still lit up. Bag was put in aft lav and monitored by FA2 Hermes. No injuries and bag with unit were left in Birmingham.

THEY WERE INFORMED TO OPEN THE PACKAGE AND DOCUMENT ALL SIX SIDES WITH PICTURES OF THE OUTER PACKAGE WHICH WAS A SMALL FEDEX BOX FOR DG STICKERS WHICH THEY FOUND NONE ATTACHED. THEY THEN PROCEEDED TO OPEN THE PACKAGE WHERE THEY FOUND AN EMPTY .22 WMR AMMO PACKAGING THAT WAS USED AS PACKING MATERIAL THAT WAS HOLDING A WHITE FEDEX PAK THERE WERE NO DG STICKERS AFFIXED TO THE FEDEX PAK AT ALL. THEY OPENED THE FEDEX PAK AND IT CONTAINED 10 BOXES OF .22 WMR AMMO, 50 CARTRIDGES PER BOX. THERE WAS NO OTHER PACKING MATERIAL INSIDE THE FEDEX PAK OTHER THAN THE 10 BOXES OF AMMO. ALL STEPS WERE DOCUMENTD THOUGH PHOTOS AND SENT TO DANGEROUS GOODS ADMINISTRATION. PACKAGE IS BEING HELD FOR FURTHER INSTRUCTION.
